.TH "SANITIZERCONFIG" "3JS" "January 16, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
SanitizerConfig \- SanitizerConfig
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]SanitizerConfig\f[B]\f[R] dictionary of the HTML
Sanitizer API specifies what elements, attributes and comments are
allowed or should be removed when inserting strings of HTML into an
\f[CR]Element\f[R] or \f[CR]ShadowRoot\f[R], or when parsing an HTML
string into a \f[CR]Document\f[R].
.PP
Note that normally \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] instances are used instead of
\f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] objects, as they are more efficient to share
and modify.
.SH INSTANCE PROPERTIES
.TP
\f[B]elements\f[R]
An array indicating the elements to allow when sanitizing HTML,
optionally also specifying their allowed or removed attributes.
.RS
.PP
Each element can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the element.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the element.
The default namespace is
\f[CR]\(dqhttp://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\(dq\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]attributes\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An array indicating the attributes to allow on this (allowed) element
when sanitizing HTML.
.RS
.PP
Each attribute can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the attribute.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the attribute, which defaults to
\f[CR]null\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]removeAttributes\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An array indicating the attributes to remove on this (allowed) element
when sanitizing HTML.
.RS
.PP
Each attribute can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the attribute.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the attribute, which defaults to
\f[CR]null\f[R].
.RE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]removeElements\f[R]
An array indicating the elements to remove when sanitizing HTML.
.RS
.PP
Each element can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the element.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the element.
The default namespace is
\f[CR]\(dqhttp://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\(dq\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]replaceWithChildrenElements\f[R]
An array indicating the elements to replace with their content when
sanitizing HTML.
This is primarily used to strip styles from text (for example, you could
use this to change \f[CR]<b>some text</b>\f[R] to \f[CR]some text\f[R]).
.RS
.PP
Each element can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the element.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the element.
The default namespace is
\f[CR]\(dqhttp://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\(dq\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]attributes\f[R]
An array indicating the attributes to allow when sanitizing HTML.
.RS
.PP
Each attribute can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the attribute.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the attribute, which defaults to
\f[CR]null\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]removeAttributes\f[R]
An array indicating the attributes to remove from elements when
sanitizing HTML.
.RS
.PP
Each attribute can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the attribute.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the attribute, which defaults to
\f[CR]null\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]comments\f[R]
\f[CR]true\f[R] if comments are allowed, and \f[CR]false\f[R] if they
are to be removed.
.TP
\f[B]dataAttributes\f[R]
\f[CR]true\f[R] if all \f[CR]data\-*\f[R] attributes will be allowed (in
which case \f[CR]data\-*\f[R] attributes must not be listed in the
\f[CR]attributes\f[R] array).
If \f[CR]false\f[R], any \f[CR]data\-*\f[R] attributes to be allowed
must be listed in the \f[CR]attributes\f[R] array.
.SH DESCRIPTION
A \f[B]\f[CB]SanitizerConfig\f[B]\f[R] specifies what elements,
attributes and comments are allowed or should be removed when inserting
strings of HTML into an \f[CR]Element\f[R] or \f[CR]ShadowRoot\f[R], or
when parsing an HTML string into a \f[CR]Document\f[R].
.PP
An instance of this type can be passed to the \f[CR]Sanitizer()\f[R]
constructor to configure a \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R], and is returned by
\f[CR]Sanitizer.get()\f[R].
It can also be passed as the \f[CR]option.sanitizer\f[R] parameter when
calling the sanitization methods:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]setHTML()\f[R] or \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] on
\f[CR]Element\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]setHTML()\f[R] or \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] on
\f[CR]ShadowRoot\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Document.parseHTML()\f[R] or \f[CR]Document.parseHTMLUnsafe()\f[R]
static methods.
.SS Valid configuration
The configuration object structure allows for the declaration of filter
options that are contradictory or redundant, such as specifying an
element in both allow and remove lists, or listing an attribute in a
list multiple times.
In order to avoid any ambiguity, methods that take a
\f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] instance require that a \f[I]valid\f[R]
configuration object be passed, and will throw a \f[CR]TypeError\f[R] if
an invalid configuration is used.
.PP
In a valid sanitizer configuration:
.IP \(bu 2
Either the \f[CR]elements\f[R] or \f[CR]removeElements\f[R] array may be
defined, but not both.
.RS 2
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] It is impossible to define per\-element attributes if
the \f[CR]removeElements\f[R] array is defined, because these are added
to elements in the \f[CR]elements\f[R] array.
.RE
.RE
.IP \(bu 2
Either the global \f[CR]attributes\f[R] or \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R]
array may be defined, but not both
.IP \(bu 2
The \f[CR]replaceWithChildrenElements\f[R] array, if defined, may not
have any elements in common with \f[CR]elements\f[R] or
\f[CR]removeElements\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
No array may contain duplicate elements or attributes
.IP \(bu 2
If the global \f[CR]attributes\f[R] array is defined:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
An element may define any or none of \f[CR]attributes\f[R] and
\f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
An element\(cqs \f[CR]attributes\f[R] must not share any values in
common with the global \f[CR]attributes\f[R] array
.IP \(bu 2
An element\(cqs \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R] array may only contain
values that are also present in the global \f[CR]attributes\f[R] array.
.IP \(bu 2
If \f[CR]dataAttributes\f[R] is \f[CR]true\f[R] the global and element
attribute arrays must not contain \f[CR]data\-*\f[R] attributes (since
these will automatically be allowed).
.RE
.IP \(bu 2
If the global \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R] array is defined:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
An element may specify either \f[CR]attributes\f[R] or
\f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R], but not both
.IP \(bu 2
An element\(cqs \f[CR]attributes\f[R] or \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R]
array, depending on which (if either) is defined, must not share any
values in common with the global \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R] array.
.IP \(bu 2
The \f[CR]dataAttributes\f[R] boolean must not be defined.
.RE
.PP
The empty object \f[CR]{}\f[R] is a valid configuration.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] The conditions above are from the perspective of a web
developer.
The \c
.UR https://wicg.github.io/sanitizer-api/#sanitizerconfig-valid
validity check defined in the specification
.UE \c
\ is slightly different because it is executed after canonicalization of
the configuration, such as adding \f[CR]removeElements\f[R] when both
are missing, and adding default namespaces.
.RE
.SS Allow and remove configurations
One of the main implications of the previous section is that a valid
configuration can specify either \f[CR]elements\f[R] or
\f[CR]removeElements\f[R] arrays (but not both) and either the
\f[CR]attributes\f[R] or \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R] arrays (but not
both).
.PP
A configuration that has the \f[CR]elements\f[R] and/or
\f[CR]attributes\f[R] arrays is referred to as an allow configuration,
as it defines the sanitization behavior in terms of the values that are
allowed to be present in the output.
A remove configuration is one that has either of
\f[CR]removeElements\f[R] and/or \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R], and
defines the behavior in terms of the values that will be removed from
the output.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Creating an \(lqallow\(rq configuration
This example shows how you might create an \(lqallow\(rq sanitizer
configuration that allows specific elements and attributes, replaces
\f[CR]<b>\f[R] elements with their children, allows comments to be
included in the output, and requires that \f[CR]data\-*\f[R] attributes
are explicitly listed in the \f[CR]attributes\f[R] array to be included.
The configuration object is passed to the \f[CR]Sanitizer()\f[R]
constructor.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [\(dqdiv\(dq, \(dqp\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq],
  attributes: [\(dqid\(dq],
  replaceWithChildrenElements: [\(dqb\(dq],
  comments: \f[B]true\f[R],
  dataAttributes: \f[B]false\f[R],
});
.EE
.SS Creating a \(lqremove\(rq configuration
This example shows how you might create a \(lqremove\(rq sanitizer
configuration that removes both elements and attributes.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  removeElements: [\(dqspan\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq],
  removeAttributes: [\(dqlang\(dq, \(dqid\(dq],
  comments: \f[B]false\f[R],
});
.EE
.SS Allow element and remove attribute configuration
This example shows how you might create a \(lqhybrid\(rq sanitizer
configuration that allows some elements and removes certain attributes.
You might similarly specify a configuration that removes elements and
allows attributes.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [\(dqspan\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq],
  removeAttributes: [\(dqlang\(dq, \(dqid\(dq],
});
.EE
.PP
Note that you having both allow and remove arrays for elements, or both
allow and remove arrays for attributes is not a valid configuration, and
would result in a \f[CR]TypeError\f[R].
.SS Invalid configurations
This sections shows a number of invalid configurations.
These will throw a \f[CR]TypeError\f[R].
.PP
Invalid because both \f[CR]elements\f[R] and \f[CR]removeElements\f[R]
are defined:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer1 = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [\(dqspan\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq],
  removeElements: [\(dqdiv\(dq, \(dqb\(dq],
});
.EE
.PP
Invalid because \f[CR]<span>\f[R] is in both \f[CR]elements\f[R] and
\f[CR]replaceWithChildrenElements\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer2 = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [\(dqspan\(dq, \(dqdiv\(dq],
  replaceWithChildrenElements: [\(dqspan\(dq],
});
.EE
.PP
Invalid because the redundant attribute \f[CR]\(dqdata\-test\(dq\f[R] is
defined when \f[CR]dataAttributes\f[R] is true:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer3 = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  attributes: [\(dqlang\(dq, \(dqid\(dq, \(dqdata\-test\(dq],
  dataAttributes: \f[B]true\f[R],
});
.EE
.PP
Invalid because it has \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R] and
\f[CR]dataAttributes\f[R] defined:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer4 = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  removeAttributes: [\(dqlang\(dq, \(dqid\(dq],
  dataAttributes: \f[B]true\f[R],
});
.EE
